# ML Efficiency

This package uses pandas/numpy/sklearn. Keep all operations vectorized.

## No row-level Python loops

```python
# BAD — iterrows / per-row apply
for _, row in df.iterrows():
    scores[i] = compute(row["hr"])
df["score"] = df.apply(lambda r: compute(r["hr"]), axis=1)

# GOOD — whole-column/array operations
scores = compute_vectorized(df["hr"].to_numpy())
df["score"] = scores
```

Avoid `.iterrows()`, `.itertuples()` with per-row logic, and `.apply()` with Python lambdas. Use numpy broadcasting, pandas vectorized methods, or sklearn batch APIs.

## Feature engineering

- Operate on whole arrays/columns, not per-window or per-sample loops where vectorization is possible.
- Use `groupby().transform()` for within-group operations (see `_add_rolling_std` in `features/build.py`).
- Signal quality functions in `features/signal_quality.py` take full numpy arrays — keep this pattern.

## Model code

- Use sklearn batch APIs (`fit`, `predict_proba`) on full matrices.
- Cross-validation via `GroupKFold.split()` — never manually split by iterating subjects.
- For priors, prefer pre-computed columns over per-row lookup when building feature tables.

## System-wide thinking

- Push filtering and aggregation into SQL (via `app/explore.py`) rather than loading entire tables into memory.
- Avoid materializing intermediate DataFrame copies — chain operations or use in-place where safe.
- Window building over sessions is acceptable (inherently sequential per subject), but per-window feature math must stay vectorized within each batch.
